00:33:31,921 --> 00:33:33,298
Scott: And it's actually a game of skill.

696
00:33:34,241 --> 00:33:44,732
Rym: It's also a good game to make your friends feel really stupid, especially if you've practiced, because if you break it open and figure out what's on all the dice, there are certain words that are very likely to be there and words that

697
00:33:44,772 --> 00:33:49,920
Scott: are also words that people that are likely to be there that are words that people are unlikely to know.

698
00:33:50,266 --> 00:33:50,499
Rym: Yeah.

699
00:33:50,723 --> 00:33:51,939
Scott: And you could be like, yes, a word.

700
00:33:52,100 --> 00:33:55,215
Scott: And then what you do is you just write your words down on paper while you're playing the game.

701
00:33:55,601 --> 00:33:58,960
Scott: And at the very end, because of the timer, you can't dispute while the timer's running.

702
00:33:59,344 --> 00:34:00,799
Scott: You could dispute after you're done.

703
00:34:01,440 --> 00:34:03,059
Scott: And then someone would be like, that word doesn't count.

704
00:34:03,140 --> 00:34:03,605
Scott: And then you get.

705
00:34:03,706 --> 00:34:04,880
Scott: then you get the dictionary out.

706
00:34:04,985 --> 00:34:05,220
Scott: Right.

707
00:34:05,681 --> 00:34:11,739
Scott: And actually, that's what I kind of like about Boggle is that any challenges or anything weird like that only matter at the end when you have time.

708
00:34:11,841 --> 00:34:13,539
Scott: And it's not a pain in the ass to figure them out.

709
00:34:13,699 --> 00:34:21,719
Rym: Unlike I don't mind Scrabble and the way it does it, because the Scrabble, it's more like the challenge in football or something like, do I challenge it or not?

710
00:34:21,780 --> 00:34:22,598
Rym: I have to make a call.

711
00:34:23,103 --> 00:34:23,638
Scott: I like that.

712
00:34:23,860 --> 00:34:32,239
Scott: But, you know, it still interrupts the game in Scrabble, which is I don't like the penalties not big enough for getting caught and the reward for catching someone is not big enough.

713
00:34:32,620 --> 00:34:33,000
Scott: That's true.

714
00:34:33,159 --> 00:34:37,320
Rym: And in fact, it should be like you get punched in the face and you have to give up a foul.

715
00:34:37,620 --> 00:34:38,760
Scott: I mean, look at football, right?

716
00:34:38,820 --> 00:34:42,020
Scott: In football, if you challenge and you're correct, you just win.

717
00:34:42,322 --> 00:34:43,320
Scott: You get your challenge, right?

718
00:34:43,380 --> 00:34:44,900
Scott: If you're challenging, you're false.

719
00:34:45,020 --> 00:34:47,239
Scott: You lose a time out in Scrabble.

720
00:34:47,822 --> 00:34:50,018
Scott: If you challenge falsely, don't you lose a turn?

721
00:34:50,762 --> 00:34:50,911
Scott: Right.

722
00:34:51,141 --> 00:34:52,119
Scott: That's a huge penalty.

723
00:34:52,621 --> 00:34:55,480
Rym: Not near the end of the game where you don't have any you don't have shit to play anyway.

724
00:34:55,821 --> 00:34:56,359
Scott: That's true.

725
00:34:56,540 --> 00:35:05,399
Scott: But if you challenge and you're if you get challenged, all that happens is you take your tiles off the board and you lose the turn.

726
00:35:05,500 --> 00:35:06,499
Rym: Are you sure that's all that happens?

727
00:35:06,804 --> 00:35:07,172
Scott: I don't know.

728
00:35:07,984 --> 00:35:08,820
Scott: That's what I remember.

729
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:09,880
Scott: It might not be correct.

730
00:35:10,020 --> 00:35:10,818
Scott: Someone can correct me.

731
00:35:10,940 --> 00:35:15,260
Rym: I mean, it might be a situation like Monopoly where fucking no one knows how Monopoly is actually played.

732
00:35:15,560 --> 00:35:20,540
Scott: The penalty for challenging needs to be less than the penalty for actually getting successfully challenged.

733
00:35:20,740 --> 00:35:25,379
Rym: I think the penalty should be pretty high, but the penalty for being caught should be even higher.

734
00:35:25,700 --> 00:35:26,320
Scott: That's what I'm saying.

735
00:35:26,601 --> 00:35:32,520
Scott: The penalty for fucking up and getting caught should be a lot worse than the penalty for challenging falsely.

736
00:35:33,100 --> 00:35:36,839
Scott: That way, because otherwise people are going to hesitate to challenge when they should.

737
00:35:38,021 --> 00:35:38,839
Rym: So Scrabble hint.

738
00:35:39,140 --> 00:35:39,376
Rym: Pro tip.

739
00:35:40,341 --> 00:35:43,120
Rym: If you want to win at Scrabble, trick all of your friends.

740
00:35:43,200 --> 00:35:46,900
Rym: Be like, yeah, let's use the OED, the Oxford English Dictionary on a bridge.

741
00:35:47,724 --> 00:35:49,060
Rym: And they'll probably be like, yeah, whatever.

742
00:35:49,161 --> 00:35:50,620
Rym: We don't care what dictionary we'll just play.

743
00:35:50,941 --> 00:35:53,160
Rym: And then just fucking make words up.

744
00:35:53,320 --> 00:35:54,379
Rym: Odds are they're in there.

745
00:35:54,801 --> 00:36:03,240
Scott: Yeah, I mean, I used L-A-Z-E-R and I was like, I was like, I looked up and it was like, you know, it was like archaic something, something.

746
00:36:03,340 --> 00:36:04,139
Rym: It was Lazar.

747
00:36:04,580 --> 00:36:07,080
Rym: And then Lazar was an archaic form of Lazar.

748
00:36:07,200 --> 00:36:10,080
Rym: And I forget the definition, but it's got to just spell those.

749
00:36:10,220 --> 00:36:12,380
Scott: There's no way that those are in the Scrabble dictionary.

750
00:36:12,781 --> 00:36:18,440
Scott: They're only in the OED because it's got every fucking word and every root of every English word imaginable.

751
00:36:18,542 --> 00:36:18,668
Scott: Yeah.

752
00:36:19,020 --> 00:36:22,040
Scott: But also you just write any old thing in there and you'll you'll get a point.

753
00:36:22,260 --> 00:36:23,200
Rym: You want to win at Scrabble.

754
00:36:23,461 --> 00:36:27,288
Rym: You've pretty much got a big vocabulary, but everyone assumes that's the only thing you need.

755
00:36:27,640 --> 00:36:29,100
Scott: That is actually the least important skill.

756
00:36:29,120 --> 00:36:32,920
Scott: You need to memorize these very specific two letter words for Scrabble.

757
00:36:33,222 --> 00:36:34,339
Rym: Not every two letter word.

758
00:36:34,460 --> 00:36:38,780
Rym: There's only twenty six times twenty six and most of those aren't even words.

759
00:36:39,252 --> 00:36:39,400
Scott: Yeah.

760
00:36:39,520 --> 00:36:43,080
Scott: You know, you have to memorize all of the two letter words and then you can win.

761
00:36:43,321 --> 00:36:45,360
Scott: You'll have to be way better at Scrabble than anybody.

762
00:36:45,520 --> 00:36:46,999
Rym: All the two letter words, if you can.

763
00:36:47,520 --> 00:36:49,399
Rym: Pretty much every weird three letter word.

764
00:36:49,962 --> 00:36:54,880
Scott: And every word that has like you, you know, because there's a lot of them, like you, you eat, right?

765
00:36:54,960 --> 00:36:55,456
Scott: Is not a word.

766
00:36:55,844 --> 00:36:56,920
Scott: There's all sorts of crazy.

767
00:36:57,120 --> 00:36:58,600
Rym: Well, that's the word in Spanish.

768
00:36:58,980 --> 00:36:59,080
Rym: Yeah.

769
00:36:59,161 --> 00:37:05,399
Scott: But I mean, there's all sorts of crazy things that are words that you wouldn't realize are words, you know, that you can score big points on.

770
00:37:06,021 --> 00:37:12,260
Scott: And because they're not a word that people use every day, most people would never even use them in Scrabble unless they're Scrabble players.

771
00:37:12,360 --> 00:37:19,659
Scott: And that's what bothers me is that Boggle is actually a game of mostly your actual vocabulary because it's all about speed.

772
00:37:20,561 --> 00:37:24,400
Scott: So you can't do a two letter word in Boggle, I don't think.

773
00:37:25,061 --> 00:37:30,800
Scott: But Scrabble isn't about just your regular old everyday vocabulary and how big it is.

774
00:37:31,243 --> 00:37:33,060
Scott: It's also and there's no timer either.

775
00:37:33,601 --> 00:37:37,920
Scott: It's mostly about did you memorize these specific Scrabble things?

776
00:37:38,141 --> 00:37:42,919
Scott: So it's like even if you're better at vocabulary, you might lose to someone who's just better at Scrabble.

777
00:37:43,140 --> 00:37:44,660
Rym: Now, to be fair, a lot of games are like that.

778
00:37:45,323 --> 00:37:53,500
Rym: Even if someone's really smart, if I've just played Puerto Rico a shit ton more than them, I am much more likely to win Puerto Rico because I know Puerto Rico specific things.

779
00:37:53,800 --> 00:37:54,200
Scott: That's true.

780
00:37:54,680 --> 00:37:58,960
Rym: But Scrabble, I guess, just tricks a lot of people who think like I used to think I never played Scrabble.

781
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:00,540
Rym: I was like, oh, I have an awesome vocabulary.

782
00:38:00,640 --> 00:38:01,720
Rym: I'll fucking rock this game.

783
00:38:02,163 --> 00:38:03,819
Rym: And instead of rocking, I got wrecked.

784
00:38:04,602 --> 00:38:07,120
Rym: I mean, neither one of those words on the triple word score.

785
00:38:07,220 --> 00:38:12,238
Scott: Yeah, I mean, that's a general problem when you have a game of knowledge versus a game of skill.

786
00:38:12,680 --> 00:38:18,640
Rym: Scrabble, there's some decisions to be made, but isn't a vocabulary game by definition, a game of skill or game of knowledge.

787
00:38:19,003 --> 00:38:20,258
Rym: How many words do you know?

788
00:38:20,500 --> 00:38:25,460
Scott: Well, no, because in Boggle has the skill of quickly recognizing them because the timer is involved.

789
00:38:25,661 --> 00:38:27,520
Rym: I think knowing the words is equally important.

790
00:38:27,740 --> 00:38:30,100
Scott: It is equally important, but there is a skill factor.

791
00:38:30,221 --> 00:38:33,620
Scott: But, you know, Scrabble is just mostly knowledge.

792
00:38:33,620 --> 00:38:37,420
Scott: It's like 90 percent knowledge, 10 percent skill of picking the right spots.

793
00:38:37,640 --> 00:38:38,438
Rym: But see, I wanted it.

794
00:38:39,223 --> 00:38:45,180
Rym: I guess my my assumption when I first played Scrabble as a kid was I assumed that it was testing just knowledge.

795
00:38:45,540 --> 00:38:46,660
Rym: How great is your vocabulary?

796
00:38:46,900 --> 00:38:49,759
Rym: Yeah, I got wrecked because it tested these other skills I didn't think about.

797
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:52,919
Rym: Yeah, of course, back then I thought Monopoly was a good game.

798
00:38:53,961 --> 00:39:02,220
Scott: The other thing about Scrabble is that it does have a luck factor, which, you know, you don't you don't think is significant because there's so many tiles in the bag and you keep drawing.

799
00:39:02,623 --> 00:39:04,140
Scott: But it's actually pretty significant.

800
00:39:04,261 --> 00:39:10,399
Scott: Someone always gets screwed with useless letters and someone else always gets a really good word and it's just complete luck.

801
00:39:10,580 --> 00:39:12,999
Scott: Whereas in Boggle, you're all looking at the same thing.

802
00:39:13,321 --> 00:39:18,699
Scott: So you could you know, you have equal chances of winning, which I think is actually makes a little bit more fair.

803
00:39:18,960 --> 00:39:25,100
Rym: Scrabble also has the the mechanics of the board itself, and you've got the strategy of blocking or building out.

804
00:39:25,480 --> 00:39:26,184
Scott: Yeah, but it's so.

805
00:39:26,305 --> 00:39:31,139
Scott: it's so obvious because the only thing you have to you basically do whatever move you can find that gets you the most points.

806
00:39:31,683 --> 00:39:33,675
Scott: And the only thing is, well, you go in order.

807
00:39:34,700 --> 00:39:37,300
Rym: Only question is the same strategy as Carcassonne.

808
00:39:37,701 --> 00:39:39,580
Rym: First, do the most for yourself.

809
00:39:39,761 --> 00:39:45,680
Rym: If you cannot do enough for yourself for it to matter, go down a notch and hurt someone else as much as you can.

810
00:39:45,800 --> 00:39:47,500
Scott: You can't really hurt someone else in Scrabble.

811
00:39:47,640 --> 00:39:52,460
Scott: What you can do is you can look at their tiles and figure out what you can look at their tiles unless you're cheating.

812
00:39:52,540 --> 00:39:57,100
Scott: But you can go into the spot that's the easiest to go to make it hard for anyone else to go.

813
00:39:58,141 --> 00:40:08,180
Scott: And you can also say, oh, this move is three points less than that move, but it makes it really hard for anyone to use that triple word score, which it will otherwise be made available.

814
00:40:08,300 --> 00:40:14,339
Scott: So I'll do that to, you know, make it harder for other players rather than, oh, man, this move gets me a ton of points.

815
00:40:14,483 --> 00:40:14,979
Scott: But you know what?

816
00:40:15,080 --> 00:40:18,980
Scott: It puts this E right out there where anyone can get a triple word score way easy.

817
00:40:19,101 --> 00:40:21,420
Scott: So it actually adds up to less points in total for me.

818
00:40:21,580 --> 00:40:24,760
Rym: You know, left right actually matters a lot in Scrabble, too.

819
00:40:25,023 --> 00:40:25,360
Rym: It does.

820
00:40:25,441 --> 00:40:27,800
Scott: Going first, you get the double word score right at the beginning.

821
00:40:28,282 --> 00:40:30,120
Rym: You know, that's not a double word score.

822
00:40:30,181 --> 00:40:30,858
Rym: That's just a star.

823
00:40:31,224 --> 00:40:32,260
Scott: No, that's double word score.

824
00:40:32,400 --> 00:40:33,100
Rym: No, it's not.

825
00:40:33,221 --> 00:40:34,440
Scott: Yeah, it is colored the same.

826
00:40:34,500 --> 00:40:35,699
Rym: You're not supposed to count it like that.

827
00:40:35,840 --> 00:40:36,820
Scott: Actually, you are really.

828
00:40:37,729 --> 00:40:38,599
Scott: I'm pretty sure you are.

829
00:40:38,741 --> 00:40:39,399
Rym: Let's look it up right now.

830
00:40:48,442 --> 00:40:52,400
Rym: A player begins the game by placing a word on the star square at the center of the board.

831
00:40:52,800 --> 00:40:55,180
Rym: The star square acts as a double word score.

832
00:40:55,541 --> 00:41:00,460
Rym: I said the star square does not act as a double word score for subsequent players.

833
00:41:00,561 --> 00:41:01,079
Rym: So you were right.

834
00:41:01,364 --> 00:41:02,319
Scott: Yes, that's correct.

835
00:41:02,720 --> 00:41:04,500
Scott: Whoever goes first gets a free double word score.

836
00:41:04,781 --> 00:41:08,319
Scott: And then it's really hard to get a double word score immediately off of that.

837
00:41:08,961 --> 00:41:11,359
Scott: So and it's like a two player game.

838
00:41:11,803 --> 00:41:13,460
Scott: Then that's in a four player game.

839
00:41:13,581 --> 00:41:16,380
Scott: It actually sort of balances out, but not in a two player game.

840
00:41:16,581 --> 00:41:20,499
Scott: Going first is a pretty good advantage, depending on the tiles you initially draw to.

841
00:41:21,122 --> 00:41:27,870
Scott: If you initially draw shit tiles that could actually screw you because your first word will be like at or something like that, you know.

842
00:41:29,590 --> 00:41:40,989
Rym: Honestly, though, Scrabble aside, I mean, everyone knows Scrabble, but a lot of my favorite games in the genre of knowledge and words and that sort of stuff, I guess not just knowledge, because that would also include like Trivial Pursuit and all that BS.

843
00:41:41,490 --> 00:41:41,968
Scott: Yeah, I don't like that.

844
00:41:42,351 --> 00:41:45,590
Rym: We should do a show on that at some point, but that's way out of the scope of this.

845
00:41:45,690 --> 00:41:46,810
Scott: Yeah, we're looking at word games here.

846
00:41:47,010 --> 00:41:52,890
Rym: We got some obscure or at least relatively obscure games of that ilk that I don't think many of you have played that you can get a hold of.

847
00:41:53,010 --> 00:41:55,209
Rym: They're actually pretty fun, like like Probe.

848
00:41:55,591 --> 00:42:00,609
Scott: Well, Probe is this game that like my grandma had in the closet that like my mom had when she was a kid.

849
00:42:00,831 --> 00:42:02,570
Rym: And basically your grandma probed you in the closet.

850
00:42:03,051 --> 00:42:03,655
Scott: It's a really.

851
00:42:03,856 --> 00:42:06,290
Scott: it's a probe is great for making jokes about probes.

852
00:42:08,092 --> 00:42:10,910
Scott: It's this really old game that I don't think has been reprinted in forever.

853
00:42:11,312 --> 00:42:13,430
Scott: And what it is, it's versus Hangman.

854
00:42:13,450 --> 00:42:13,701
Scott: Right.

855
00:42:13,991 --> 00:42:16,610
Scott: So you make a word and you added these cards.

856
00:42:16,730 --> 00:42:24,629
